Diagnosis . Males and females of this species are most similar to
A. feredayi
(see Diagnosis above). Females differ distinctly from
A. melanura
(as interpreted here based on a female found in Queensland ) by the shape of the epigynum, which forms a simple subquadrate scape and distinct lateral arches in
A. higginsii
( Fig. 5D ), but a broad U-shaped lip and lateral lobes in
A. melanura
( Fig. 10E ).

Variation . Females (n = 70): total length, 10.6–24.1; males (n = 13): total length, 2.2–3.6. Females can vary in colour, often without the darker brown features on carapace and sternum and dorsal, ventral and lateral abdomen ( Fig. 8A ). Venter colour varies in the amount of the dark brown dusky guanine spots. In females, the projections on the tail are very variable, from elongated finger-like prongs ( Figs. 5C , 8A ) to small tubercles ( Fig. 8D ), just like
A. feredayi
.

subSubSection.paragraph:
Remarks. Two females of
A. higginsii
in the BMNH (1915.3.5.443, 1915.3.5.740) include the typical labels as used by L. Koch and appear therefore to be part of the L. Koch collection that has been purchased by the NHM from the Museum Godeffroy (see e.g.
Baehr et al. , 2017
). However, both are labelled ‘Sydney’, not Darling Downs, the type locality of the species and are therefore unlikely to represent the holotype .

The spelling
Arachnura higginsi
has been frequently used for this species (see list of synonyms above); however, the correct spelling is
Arachnura higginsii (L. Koch, 1872 )
. This is in accordance with article 33.4 in the fourth edition of the International Code of Zoological Nomenclature ( International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature 1999 ), which states the change from -ii to -i is a subsequent incorrect spelling (but see FAQ section of World Spider Catalog 2019 ).

Life history and habitat preferences. Mature males have so far only been found from mid-summer to autumn (November, and January to April) peaking in February. Mature females have been found all year round, with occasional records in August and September, then increasing in numbers to a peak in February and declining steadily after that.

Habitat descriptions found on specimen labels varied considerably, suggesting that although
A. higginsii
prefers variable open woodlands (
Banksia speciosa
,
Acacia
spp.,
Eucalyptus
spp. including Jarrah and River red-gum (
E. marginata
and
E. camaldulensis
), individuals have also been recorded from vine thickets, scree slopes and in the littoral zone on cliffs. The species is also not uncommon in cultural landscapes, for example garden and parks.
Distribution . Only known from Australia , south of ca. 24°S Latitude; present in all states except Northern Territory ( Fig. 13 ).
